Then saved this JS code as `debounce.js`:
```javascript
let buffer = Buffer.alloc(0);

function flush() {
  process.stdout.write(buffer);
  buffer.fill();
}

let id = setInterval(flush, 1000);

process.stdin.on('data', data => {
  clearInterval(id);
  buffer = Buffer.concat([buffer, data]);
  id = setInterval(flush, 1000);
});
```

Then ran this command in a normal iTerm2 tab:
```sh
tail -f /tmp/osc | node debounce.js
```

And running `imgcat` in a terminal inside Neovim I could see it in the iTerm2 terminal.

<img width="1208" alt="image" src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1270688/188531064-4b029e25-5f70-44e1-95d8-0e9e648c780a.png">

The debouncer is needed so that the whole imgcat command is sent to iTerm2 in a single write, it wouldn't work otherwise. So we will need to buffer fragments and concatenate them in a buffer before writing to terminal.

When I hidden the buffer and opened it again, it didn't call the osc callback again (osc callback is called only once). I think this should be handled in Neovim and not libvterm and I think it won't be easy because some osc commands (like showing a notification, bouncing iTerm2 icon, etc) should run only once even if the buffer is hidden and shown again, but some like the one generated by `imgcat`, should run again exactly in the same place whenever the buffer is shown again. Deciding which osc command is in which category may need collaboration with iTerm2 developer for a general and future proof solution, alternatively we can hardcode the list of the commands in the second category in Neovim's codebase.

